This Transportation Impact Study was updated to address PENNDOT’s review
comments dated October 4, 2013 and November 12, 2013. A copy of the comments and
a list of responses addressing the comments are provided in Appendix A. Additionally,
the TIS was updated to address October 23, 2013 comments from Keystone Consulting
Engineers on behalf of Hanover Township (Lehigh County). We understand through
Hanover Engineering that Allen Township has no comments on the TIS.
The Rockefeller Group Development Corporation proposes to develop an industrial
development consisting of a Regional Distribution Hub (RDH) facility and warehousing
facilities. The development will be located along Willowbrook Road north of Race Street
The development is anticipated to consist of a 1,200,000 square foot Regional
Distribution Hub and two 1,000,000 square foot warehouses. Access to the development
The Regional Distribution Hub (RDH) is anticipated to be a package distribution center,
where packages arrive, are sorted, and are sent out. There is no repackaging of items or
assembly of items associated with this facility.
The 1,200,000 square foot RDH and the two additional 1,000,000 square foot warehouse
developments are anticipated to generate approximately 14,602 daily trips, including
1,194 trips and 957 trips during the AM and PM Peak hours, respectively.
The 1,200,000 square foot RDH facility is anticipated to open in 2015 and will be served
by three accesses to Willowbrook Road. A truck-in access, a signalized full-movement
employee access, and a truck-out access are anticipated. The development is anticipated
to generate 7,460 daily trips, including 1,040 tractor-trailer trips, 580 customer delivery
vehicle trips, and 5,840 car trips each day. The RDH is anticipated to generate 608 AM
Peak hour and 437 PM Peak hour trips.
The two 1,000,000 square foot warehouse developments are anticipated to open in 2017
and will be served by four accesses to Willowbrook Road. The Southern Warehouse is
anticipated to be serviced by a truck access, an employee access, and a combined access.
The Northern Warehouse is anticipated to be accessed via the signalized RDH truck-out
access. The warehouses are anticipated to generate 7,142 daily trips, including 760 truck
trips and 6,382 car trips each day. The warehouses are anticipated to generate 586 AM
Peak hour and 520 PM Peak hour trips.
The following improvements will be constructed along the study roadways to
accommodate the site-generated traffic from the proposed developments:
Willowbrook Road will be widened from Race Street to the RDH Truck-
Out / Northern Warehouse driveway from one lane in each direction to two
lanes in each direction. Left-turn lanes to accommodate the left-turn
movements at the RDH and warehouse driveways will be provided.
Race Street will be widened from Willowbrook Road to Airport Road from
2 lanes to 5 lanes with two lanes in each direction and a center turn lane.
A third southbound through lane will be constructed along Airport Road
from Race Street to the westbound on-ramp to US 22.

This Transportation Impact Study was updated to address PENNDOT’s review
comments dated October 4, 2013 and November 12, 2013. A copy of the comments and
a list of responses addressing the comments are provided in Appendix A. Additionally,
the TIS was updated to address October 23, 2013 comments from Keystone Consulting
Engineers on behalf of Hanover Township (Lehigh County). We understand through
Hanover Engineering that Allen Township has no comments on the TIS.
The Rockefeller Group Development Corporation proposes to develop an industrial
development consisting of a Regional Distribution Hub (RDH) facility and warehousing
facilities. The development will be located along Willowbrook Road north of Race
Street (SR 1004) in Allen Township, Northampton County.
The development is anticipated to consist of a 1,200,000 square foot Regional
Distribution Hub and two 1,000,000 square foot warehouses. Access to the development
The Regional Distribution Hub is a proposed package distribution center where packages
arrive, are sorted, and are sent out to consumers. The RDH does not store any packages.
The process center operates on a 24-hour basis. There is no repackaging of items or
assembly of items associated with this facility.
The Regional Distribution Hub is anticipated to be open in 2015 while the full
development (with the two warehouses) is expected to be occupied in 2017. As required
by PENNDOT, the design horizon year for the project (five years after full build–out) is
This Transportation Impact Study (TIS) has been prepared to analyze any traffic impacts
on the surrounding road network that might arise from this development, and to provide
recommendations for mitigation of any traffic impacts. A TIS scoping application was
prepared and submitted to PENNDOT. The approved TIS Scoping Application is
attached in Appendix A. The scope of the study includes the following intersections:
Airport Road (SR 0987) & Lehigh Valley International Airport Driveway
Airport Road (SR 0987) & Postal Road / Avenue A
Willowbrook Road & RDH Truck-in Access/Southern Warehouse Truck Access
Willowbrook Road & Southern Warehouse Employee Access
Willowbrook Road & RDH Employee Access/Southern Warehouse Combined
Willowbrook Road & RDH Truck-out Access/Northern Warehouse Access
The study area intersections are presented in Figure 2.
This TIS investigates the Levels of Service (LOS) for the Existing Conditions and the
2015, 2017, and 2022 “No-Build” conditions for the above-referenced intersections.
These analyses predict the operational characteristics of the intersections without the
proposed development. In addition, the Levels of Service for the 2015, 2017, and 2022
“Build” conditions are analyzed. These analyses predict the operational characteristics of
the intersections with the traffic generation from the proposed development.

of Race Street (SR 1004). The following provides a description of the roadways that are
Race Street (SR 1004) is oriented in an east/west direction and is generally a two-lane
roadway that provides one travel lane in each direction. Between the intersection of
Airport Road and Old Airport Road, Race Street provides two lanes in the westbound
direction. Race Street is classified as an Urban Minor Arterial roadway with a Suburban
Corridor Community Arterial typology. This roadway is under the jurisdiction of
PENNDOT. The posted speed limit is 45 MPH along Race Street.
Airport Road (SR 0987) is generally oriented in a north/south direction. Within the study
area, Airport Road is generally a four-lane roadway providing two travel lanes in each
direction. Airport Road is also known as PA Route 987 and is classified as an Urban
Principal Arterial roadway with a Suburban Corridor Regional Arterial typology. This
roadway is under the jurisdiction of PENNDOT. Access to Lehigh Valley International
Airport is provided via Airport Road. The posted speed limit is 40 MPH along Airport
Schoenersville Road (SR 1009) is a north/south roadway. Schoenersville Road provides
two travel lanes in each direction south of Airport Road and one lane north of Airport
Road. Schoenersville Road is classified as an Urban Minor Arterial with a Suburban
Corridor Regional Arterial typology. The roadway is under the jurisdiction of
PENNDOT. The posted speed limit along Schoenersville Road is 45 MPH.

within the study area. Willowbrook Road is classified as a Rural Minor Collector and

City Line Road extends in an east/west direction and provides one travel lane in each

Postal Road generally extends in an east/west roadway and provides one travel lane in

Collector typology. The roadway is under the jurisdiction of Hanover Township, Lehigh

Avenue A generally extends in an east/west direction and provides one travel lane in each

The roadway is under the jurisdiction of the City of Bethlehem. The speed limit along
Avenue A is posted at 35 MPH.
West Bullshead Road generally extends in an east/west direction and provides one travel

Howertown Road. Approaching Howertown Road, West Bullshead Road becomes 4
Street. West Bullshead Road is classified as a Rural Local roadway and has a Local
Road typology. The roadway is under the jurisdiction of Allen Township within the

Capacity analyses were performed to evaluate the traffic conditions at each of the studied
intersections. Signalized and unsignalized intersections are analyzed for their ability to
serve traffic volumes and to determine the level of operational service for each movement
at an intersection. The analyses in this study were performed using the latest Highway
Capacity Manual (HCM 2010) methodology using the Synchro v8.0, software developed
by Trafficware Inc. Synchro is computerized software widely accepted as an analysis
tool for signalized and unsignalized intersections. PENNDOT local values from
Publication 46 (Traffic Engineering Manual) were used for Base Saturation Flow Rates,
Traffic Signal Control Calibration Parameters, Critical Headways at Two-Way Stop
Control (TWSC) intersections, and Follow-up Headway at TWSC intersections. The
local values are found in Publication 46 Exhibits 10-9 to 10-12.
Level of Service is generally defined in terms of average control delay per vehicle, which
is a measure of loss of travel time. Delay is dependent on a number of factors, including
width of the roadways, number of lanes, turning volumes, heavy vehicle (truck) volumes,
the green time to cycle length ratio (g/c), and the volume to capacity (v/c) ratio for the
approach in question. The criteria for the various level of service designations are as
In addition to the delay criterion, when a movement, approach, or intersection operates
with a v/c ratio greater than 1 (volume exceeds capacity), the LOS is identified as F,
Level of Service is defined in terms of average control delay per vehicle, which is a
measure of loss of travel time. Unsignalized intersection analyses are based on the gap
acceptance theory, which relies on three basic elements, including the size and
availability of gaps in the major traffic stream, the usefulness of the gaps to the individual
minor stream drivers, and the relative priority of the various traffic stream movements.
In addition to the delay criterion, when a movement, approach, or intersection operates
with a v/c ratio greater than 1 (volume exceeds capacity), the LOS is identified as F,
Levels of Service range from values A though F as indicated above. Level of Service A
is considered free flow, where the motorist can make any movement with little or no
delay. Level of Service F is considered failure, where traffic is proceeding so slowly that
it causes frustration for the motorist. Levels of Service B through E indicate increasing
delays for each level. Further definitions of Levels of Service are in found in Appendix
E. The LOS is calculated for each movement of the approach; i.e., a left turn lane could
be operating at LOS F while the through lane could be operating at LOS B. Generally, if
a facility is found to be operating at a LOS C or higher in rural areas or LOS D or higher
in urban areas, the facility is considered to be adequate. These levels of service allow the
motorist to proceed through an intersection without serious delays.

Based on PENNDOT’s District 5 Growth Factors for September 2012 to July 2013, the
rate for an urban non-interstate in Lehigh County is 1.13 percent per year while the
Northampton County rate is 1.57 percent per year. While the development is located
within Northampton County, the proposed development is located near the Lehigh
County and Northampton County line. To prepare a conservative analysis, the growth
factors for both counties were averaged to obtain a background growth rate of 1.35
percent per year. The growth rate was compounded over 2 years (1.0272) and applied to
the 2013 existing traffic volumes depicted on Figure 4 to obtain the 2015 No-Build
Traffic Volumes shown on Figure 6. The spreadsheet containing the calculations is
included in Appendix G. As approved in the TIS Scoping Meeting Application, there are
no “other” developments to be included in this TIS.
